SIMPLE: hold
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hold
<hw>Hold</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧ld)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D.
<ets>hol</ets> hole, hollow. See <er>Hole</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The whole interior portion of a vessel below the
lower deck, in which the cargo is stowed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hold
<hw>Hold</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Held</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Holding</conjf>. <conjf>Holden</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>p.
p.</pos>, is obs. in elegant writing, though still used in legal
language.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>haldan</ets>, D. <ets>houden</ets>,
OHG. <ets>hoten</ets>, Icel. <ets>halda</ets>, Dan. <ets>holde</ets>,
Sw. <ets>h⟦aring⟧lla</ets>, <ets>Goth</ets>. <ets>haldan</ets> to feed,
tend (the cattle); of unknown origin. Gf. <er>Avast</er>, <er>Halt</er>,
<er>Hod</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to remain in a given situation, position,
or relation, within certain limits, or the like; to prevent from falling
or escaping; to sustain; to restrain; to keep in the grasp; to
retain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The loops <qex>held</qex> one curtain to another.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
xxxvi. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy right hand shall <qex>hold</qex> me.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxxxix.
10. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They all <qex>hold</qex> swords, being expert in war.</q>
<rj><qau>Cant. iii. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In vain he seeks, that having can not <qex>hold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>France, thou mayst <qex>hold</qex> a serpent by the tongue, . . .
⟦br⟧
A fasting tiger safer by the tooth,⟦br⟧
Than keep in peace that hand which thou dost <qex>hold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To retain in one's keeping; to maintain possession
of, or authority over; not to give up or relinquish; to keep; to
defend.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We mean to <qex>hold</qex> what anciently we claim⟦br⟧
Of deity or empire.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To have; to possess; to be in possession of; to
occupy; to derive title to; <as>as, to <ex>hold</ex>
office</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This noble merchant <qex>held</qex> a noble house.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of him to <qex>hold</qex> his seigniory for a yearly tribute.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now the strand, and now the plain, they <qex>held</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To impose restraint upon; to limit in motion or
action; to bind legally or morally; to confine; to restrain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We can not <qex>hold</qex> mortality's strong hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death! what do'st? O, <qex>hold</qex> thy blow.</q>
<rj><qau>Grashaw.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had not sufficient judgment and self-command to <qex>hold</qex>
his tongue.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To maintain in being or action; to carry on; to
prosecute, as a course of conduct or an argument; to continue; to
sustain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hold</qex> not thy peace, and be not still.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
lxxxiii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seedtime and harvest, heat and hoary frost,⟦br⟧
Shall <qex>hold</qex> their course.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To prosecute, have, take, or join in, as something
which is the result of united action; as to, <xex>hold</xex> a meeting,
a festival, a session, etc.; hence, to direct and bring about
officially; to conduct or preside at; <as>as, the general <ex>held</ex>
a council of war; a judge <ex>holds</ex> a court; a clergyman
<ex>holds</ex> a service.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would <qex>hold</qex> more talk with thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To receive and retain; to contain as a vessel;
<as>as, this pail <ex>holds</ex> milk</as>; hence, to be able to receive
and retain; to have capacity or containing power for.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Broken cisterns that can <qex>hold</qex> no water.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. ii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One sees more devils than vast hell can <qex>hold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To accept, as an opinion; to be the adherent of,
openly or privately; to persist in, as a purpose; to maintain; to
sustain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stand fast and <qex>hold</qex> the traditions which ye have been
taught.</q> <rj><qau>2 Thes. ii.15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But still he <qex>held</qex> his purpose to depart.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To consider; to regard; to esteem; to account; to
think; to judge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>hold</qex> him but a fool.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shall never <qex>hold</qex> that man my friend.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord will not <qex>hold</qex> him guiltless that taketh his
name in vain.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xx. 7. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To bear, carry, or manage; <as>as he <ex>holds</ex>
himself erect; he <ex>holds</ex> his head high.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let him <qex>hold</qex> his fingers thus.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To hold a wager</b></col>, <cd>to lay or hazard a
wager.</cd> <au>Swift.</au> -- <col><b>To hold forth</b></col>,
<sd>(a)</sd> <pos>v. t.</pos><cd>to offer; to exhibit; to propose; to
put forward.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The propositions which books <xex>hold
forth</xex> and pretend to teach.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Locke.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<pos>v. i.</pos> <cd>To talk at length; to harangue.</cd> -- <col><b>To
held in</b></col>, <cd>to restrain; to curd.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold in
hand</b></col>, <cd>to toy with; to keep in expectation; to have in
one's power.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, fie! to receive favors, return falsehoods,⟦br⟧
And <qex>hold</qex> a lady in <qex>hand</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Beaw. &
Fl.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To hold in play</b></col>, <cd>to keep under control; to
dally with.</cd> <au>Macaulay.</au> -- <col><b>To hold off</b></col>,
<cd>to keep at a distance.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold on</b></col>, <cd>to
hold in being, continuance or position; as, <xex>to hold</xex> a rider
<xex>on</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold one's day</b></col>, <cd>to keep
one's appointment.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> --
<col><b>To hold one's own</b></col>. <cd>To keep good one's present
condition absolutely or relatively; not to fall off, or to lose ground;
as, a ship <xex>holds her own</xex> when she does not lose ground in a
race or chase; a man <xex>holds his own</xex> when he does not lose
strength or weight.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold one's peace</b></col>,
<cd>to keep silence.</cd>- <col><b>To hold out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To extend; to offer.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Fortune <xex>holds out</xex> these
to you as rewards.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>B. Jonson.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
continue to do or to suffer; to endure.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧He can not long
<xex>hold out</xex> these pangs.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To
hold up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To raise; to lift; as, <xex>hold
up</xex> your head.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To support; to sustain.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>holds</xex> himself <xex>up</xex> in
virtue.⟦rdquo⟧<au>Sir P. Sidney.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To exhibit; to
display; as, he was <xex>held up</xex> as an example.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd>
<cd>To rein in; to check; to halt; as, <xex>hold up</xex> your
horses.</cd> <sd>(e)</sd> <cd>to rob, usually at gunpoint; -- often with
the demand to ⟦ldquo⟧hold up⟦rdquo⟧ the hands.</cd> <sd>(f)</sd> <cd>To
delay.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold water</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Literally, to retain water without leaking; hence
(<mark>Fig</mark>.), to be whole, sound, consistent, without gaps or
holes; -- commonly used in a negative sense; as, his statements will not
<xex>hold water</xex>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To hold the oars steady in the water, thus
checking the headway of a boat.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Hold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hold
<hw>Hold</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>In general, to keep one's self in a
given position or condition; to remain fixed. Hence:</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not to move; to halt; to stop; -- mostly in the
imperative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And damned be him that first cries, ⟦ldquo⟧<qex>Hold</qex>,
enough!⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not to give way; not to part or become separated; to
remain unbroken or unsubdued.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our force by land hath nobly <qex>held</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not to fail or be found wanting; to continue; to
last; to endure a test or trial; to abide; to persist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While our obedience <qex>holds</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rule <qex>holds</qex> in land as all other commodities.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not to fall away, desert, or prove recreant; to
remain attached; to cleave; -- often with <xex>with</xex>,
<xex>to</xex>, or <xex>for</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will <qex>hold</qex> to the one and despise the other.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. vi. 24</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To restrain one's self; to refrain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His dauntless heart would fain have <qex>held</qex>⟦br⟧
From weeping, but his eyes rebelled.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To derive right or title; -- generally with
<xex>of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My crown is absolute, and <qex>holds</qex> of none.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His imagination <qex>holds</qex> immediately from nature.</q>
<rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Hold on!</b></col> <col><b>Hold up!</b></col>
<cd>wait; stop; forbear.</cd> <mark>[Collog]</mark> -- <col><b>To hold
forth</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to speak in public; to harangue; to
preach.</cd> <au>L'Estrange.</au> -- <col><b>To hold in</b></col>,
<cd>to restrain one's self; as, he wanted to laugh and could hardly
<xex>hold in</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold off</b></col>, <cd>to keep
at a distance.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold on</b></col>, <cd>to keep fast
hold; to continue; to go on.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The trade <xex>held on</xex>
for many years,⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Swift.</au> -- <col><b>To hold out</b></col>,
<cd>to last; to endure; to continue; to maintain one's self; not to
yield or give way.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold over</b></col>, <cd>to remain
in office, possession, etc., beyond a certain date.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>To hold to</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To hold
with</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to take sides with, as a person or
opinion.</cd> -- <col><b>To hold together</b></col>, <cd>to be joined;
not to separate; to remain in union.</cd> <au>Dryden.</au>
<au>Locke.</au> -- <col><b>To hold up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
support one's self; to remain unbent or unbroken; as, to <xex>hold
up</xex> under misfortunes.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To cease raining; to
cease to stop; as, it <xex>holds up</xex>.</cd> <au>Hudibras.</au>
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To keep up; not to fall behind; not to lose
ground.</cd> <au>Collier.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hold
<hw>Hold</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧ld)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of holding, as in or with the hands or arms; the manner of holding,
whether firm or loose; seizure; grasp; clasp; grip; possession; -- often
used with the verbs <xex>take</xex> and <xex>lay</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ne have I not twelve pence within mine <qex>hold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou should'st lay <qex>hold</qex> upon him.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul took <qex>hold</qex> on thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take fast <qex>hold</qex> of instruction.</q> <rj><qau>Pror. iv.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The authority or ground to take or keep;
claim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The law hath yet another <qex>hold</qex> on you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Binding power and influence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fear . . . by which God and his laws take the surest <qex>hold
of</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Something that may be grasped; means of
support.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a man be upon an high place without rails or good
<qex>hold</qex>, he is ready to fall.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A place of confinement; a prison; confinement;
custody; guard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They . . . put them in <qex>hold</qex> unto the next day.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts. iv. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>King Richard, he is in the mighty <qex>hold</qex>⟦br⟧
Of Bolingbroke.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A place of security; a fortified place; a fort; a
castle; -- often called a <altname>stronghold</altname>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>New comers in an ancient <qex>hold</qex></q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A character [thus <?/] placed over
or under a note or rest, and indicating that it is to be prolonged; --
called also <altname>pause</altname>, and
<altname>corona</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>holdall</ent>⟦br⟧
